---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About Data Journal"
	description="What is Data Journal and what you will learn here."
	pubDate={new Date('March 01 2025')}
	heroImage="/blog-placeholder-about.jpg"
>
	<p>
		<strong>Data Journal</strong> is a practical reference site for people who work with data — or
		want to. It focuses on the foundational skills that come before analysis: finding data sources,
		pulling data through APIs, handling different file formats, and organizing everything into a
		clean, queryable structure.
	</p>

	<h2>What You Will Find Here</h2>
	<p>
		Every article is built around a real, repeatable task. You will not find abstract theory or
		academic definitions. Instead, each guide walks through a specific problem — like paginating
		through an API, deduplicating a CSV, or joining two tables in SQL — with working code examples
		and explanations of each step.
	</p>
	<p>
		Articles are organized as a progressive sequence. If you read them in order, you will go from
		"I have a data source I want to use" to "I have an automated pipeline that keeps my data fresh
		and organized." If you already know the basics, each article also stands on its own as a
		reference.
	</p>

	<h2>Who This Is For</h2>
	<p>
		Data Journal is written for:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Developers</strong> who need to integrate data from external APIs or files into their applications.</li>
		<li><strong>Analysts</strong> who receive messy exports and need to clean and reshape them before running queries.</li>
		<li><strong>Researchers</strong> who are collecting data from public sources and need a reproducible workflow.</li>
		<li><strong>Students</strong> who understand statistics but have never connected a script to a live data source.</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Tools and Languages</h2>
	<p>
		Most examples use <strong>Python</strong> with the standard library plus pandas and requests,
		or plain <strong>SQL</strong> (compatible with SQLite, PostgreSQL, and MySQL). Some articles
		use <strong>curl</strong> and <strong>jq</strong> for quick command-line data work.
	</p>
	<p>
		The goal is to teach transferable patterns, not to lock you into a specific tool. Once you
		understand how pagination works, you can implement it in any language. Once you know what
		a join does, you can write it in SQL or reproduce it with pandas <code>merge()</code>.
	</p>

	<h2>How to Use This Site</h2>
	<p>
		If you are starting from scratch, follow the <a href="/">Start Here</a> sequence on the home
		page. Each article links to the next in the series. If you are looking for something specific,
		use the <a href="/blog">Articles</a> index to browse by topic.
	</p>
	<p>
		Code blocks throughout the site can be copied directly. Variables like <code>YOUR_API_KEY</code>
		are always called out clearly so you know exactly what to replace.
	</p>
</Layout>
